00:00:26.260 --> 00:00:28.660
PROFESSOR: So, moving
to today's handout,

00:00:28.660 --> 00:00:32.150
we're going to talk about
crystal field theory.

00:00:32.150 --> 00:00:34.570
And we're going
to talk about how

00:00:34.570 --> 00:00:37.390
the shapes of those
orbitals can explain

00:00:37.390 --> 00:00:40.180
the special properties
of transition metals,

00:00:40.180 --> 00:00:42.790
like color and magnetism.

00:00:42.790 --> 00:00:45.250
And really, as I said,
the transition metals

00:00:45.250 --> 00:00:48.460
have amazing properties that
can be absolutely gorgeous.

00:00:48.460 --> 00:00:50.500
They can do incredible things.

00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:52.480
They're very, very
useful elements.

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:54.910
I like to think of them
as the super heroes

00:00:54.910 --> 00:00:56.650
of the periodic table.

00:00:56.650 --> 00:01:00.560
They're doing all the
really spectacular stuff.

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:02.740
So, today, we're going
to talk about colors.

00:01:02.740 --> 00:01:05.560
And we're going to talk about
whether things are magnetic,

00:01:05.560 --> 00:01:08.200
if they're paramagnetic,
or diamagnetic.

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:10.180
So, transition metals.

00:01:10.180 --> 00:01:13.840
I talked before about how
they're useful in biology.

00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:18.480
They're also useful in terms
of their beautiful colors.

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:22.240
So, in the old days before
you generated floor plans

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:24.850
and drawings for
buildings, on a computer

00:01:24.850 --> 00:01:27.130
you did blueprints
for something.

00:01:27.130 --> 00:01:31.360
And the blue in the blueprint
is actually a transition metal

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:33.010
complex.

00:01:33.010 --> 00:01:37.150
And also, currently, it's
an active area of research

00:01:37.150 --> 00:01:42.160
to design new imaging agents
to use in MRIs, or to image

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:43.780
the heart, or other things.

00:01:43.780 --> 00:01:47.170
And a lot of these also involve
transition metal complexes.

00:01:47.170 --> 00:01:49.960
And the reason why they're
useful, say, in an MRI

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:52.510
is because they can have
magnetic properties.

00:01:52.510 --> 00:01:55.340
So, scientists see
these beautiful colors.

00:01:55.340 --> 00:01:57.700
It's kind of obvious that
the transition metals often

00:01:57.700 --> 00:01:59.680
have these incredible colors.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:02.620
And they can put the
transition metals in something

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:05.792
with a magnet and see that
they have magnetic properties.

00:02:05.792 --> 00:02:07.000
So these things were obvious.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:09.789
And then chemists want to try
to understand why it's true.

00:02:09.789 --> 00:02:12.400
Why this particular metal
behaves this way, or this metal

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:14.110
has this particular color.

00:02:14.110 --> 00:02:16.390
And they like to try to
categorize them and come up

00:02:16.390 --> 00:02:19.780
with theories that
help to explain what

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:21.580
they're observing in nature.

00:02:21.580 --> 00:02:23.740
And so, today, we're
going to talk about one

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:26.380
of those theories, which
is Ligand field theory.

00:02:26.380 --> 00:02:28.660
And I'm also going to
differentiate that-- or Crystal

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:31.970
field theory and differentiate
it from Ligand field theory.

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:33.880
So both of these
theories, again,

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:38.140
are an attempt to explain the
properties that we observe.

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:40.970
And the idea behind
it is pretty simple.

00:02:40.970 --> 00:02:44.470
You have a metal ion and a
set of ligands around it.

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:49.390
And if you compare the energy
levels of that free metal ion--

00:02:49.390 --> 00:02:52.270
so here's a free metal
ion-- with that metal

00:02:52.270 --> 00:02:54.380
ion in a coordination
complex-- here

00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:57.220
is quite a pretty
coordination complex--

00:02:57.220 --> 00:03:00.100
the energy levels are different.

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:02.920
That's really all these
theories are getting at.

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:05.260
That there's a change
when you bring ligands

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:08.710
in around a transition metal.

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.650
It changes the energy
levels of those d orbitals.

00:03:11.650 --> 00:03:14.350
And if we understand how
those de-energy levels change,

00:03:14.350 --> 00:03:16.600
we can understand a lot
about the properties

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:21.760
of that particular metal in
that coordination environment.

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:25.750
So energy levels are altered.

00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:28.750
So there's these two
theories: Crystal field theory

00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:30.910
and Ligand field theory.

00:03:30.910 --> 00:03:34.840
Crystal field theory
is the more simple one.

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:40.170
It just considers the ionic
description of the metal ligand

00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:41.230
bond.

00:03:41.230 --> 00:03:44.067
And so we talked
about ionic bonds.

00:03:44.067 --> 00:03:46.150
And mostly you're just
kind of thinking about them

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:48.104
as these point charges.

00:03:48.104 --> 00:03:49.520
And you have plus,
you have minus,

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:51.820
and they attract each other.

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:54.627
Covalent bonding is a
bit more complicated.

00:03:54.627 --> 00:03:56.710
Start talking about
hybridization and other things

00:03:56.710 --> 00:03:57.670
like that.

00:03:57.670 --> 00:03:59.630
So Crystal field theory
is really simple.

00:03:59.630 --> 00:04:02.200
It just considers
the ionic nature.

00:04:02.200 --> 00:04:03.730
And it does pretty well.

00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:06.230
It can explain a lot,
but not everything.

00:04:06.230 --> 00:04:09.790
Ligand field theory has
the covalent and the ionic,

00:04:09.790 --> 00:04:11.350
so it's a more
complete description

00:04:11.350 --> 00:04:13.030
of that metal ligand bond.

00:04:13.030 --> 00:04:15.670
But this is more of
an advanced topic.

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:17.570
I just want you to
know that that exists.

00:04:17.570 --> 00:04:20.680
So if you take 503 here
in organic chemistry,

00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:22.660
we'll talk more about
Ligand field theory.

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:25.570
In this class we're just going
to do Crystal field theory.

00:04:25.570 --> 00:04:27.880
But I like Crystal field
theory because I like it

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:30.310
when something that's
pretty simple theory

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:31.720
can explain a lot.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.540
I think a lot of nature
can be explained by this.

00:04:34.540 --> 00:04:36.640
So if you really
want to understand

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:39.610
particular properties
of a specific compound,

00:04:39.610 --> 00:04:41.681
you probably want a
more complicated way

00:04:41.681 --> 00:04:42.430
to think about it.

00:04:42.430 --> 00:04:44.990
But if in general
you just want to say,

00:04:44.990 --> 00:04:48.880
why can some cobalt complexes
can be so many colors?

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:51.700
Crystal field theory works
really well for that.

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:54.430
All right, so
Crystal field theory.

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:57.730
Very simple idea behind this.

00:04:57.730 --> 00:04:59.380
It's almost
disappointing, I think.

00:04:59.380 --> 00:04:59.980
But it's OK.

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:01.960
You can go, yeah we're
studying, you know,

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:03.670
Crystal field theory in class.

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:06.190
Yeah, you don't have to
tell people that it's

00:05:06.190 --> 00:05:08.450
a really, very simple idea.

00:05:08.450 --> 00:05:12.310
So the idea is that the
ligands are negative charges.

00:05:12.310 --> 00:05:15.550
They're like this big
blob of negativity.

00:05:15.550 --> 00:05:19.570
And those ligands,
with their lone pairs,

00:05:19.570 --> 00:05:21.310
their negativeness
or negative charge--

00:05:21.310 --> 00:05:24.970
they got those extra lone pair
electrons-- are going to be

00:05:24.970 --> 00:05:28.780
repulsive to those d orbitals.

00:05:28.780 --> 00:05:30.330
Negative point
charges, you bring

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:34.380
a d orbital, And a lone pair,
and there's some repulsion.

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:36.090
That's basically it.

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:38.160
Negative point charge repulsion.

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:39.930
That's all that you
have to think about

00:05:39.930 --> 00:05:41.430
with Crystal field theory.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:45.000
So it sounds really impressive
to tell people you're

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.190
doing Crystal field theory.

00:05:47.190 --> 00:05:50.460
And you can neglect to
mention that it's just

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:54.090
a really very, very simple idea
that, sort of, negative charges

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:54.810
repel each other.

00:05:54.810 --> 00:05:56.395
That's really all it is.

00:05:56.395 --> 00:05:58.020
All right, so we're
going to talk first

00:05:58.020 --> 00:06:00.240
about the octahedral case.

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:02.820
And then we're going to get
into some other geometries

00:06:02.820 --> 00:06:05.010
on Friday, so that's
going to be exciting.

00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:07.678
But here's our
octahedral molecule.

00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:14.580
And here we have it, here.

00:06:14.580 --> 00:06:19.140
And I can think about the metal
in the middle, M to the N plus.

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:23.100
So this just indicates it's
any metal and to the oxidation

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:24.480
number.

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:26.400
And the black balls,
here, are the ligands

00:06:26.400 --> 00:06:29.470
and we can think of those
as negative charges.

00:06:29.470 --> 00:06:35.970
So here, we have drawn sort
of this octohedral shape

00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:38.490
around the metal in the middle.

00:06:38.490 --> 00:06:40.500
And we can think
about these NH3 groups

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:41.990
as these negative point charges.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:45.430
So these dots here are
negative point charges.

00:06:45.430 --> 00:06:47.940
And so now if we think about
the shapes of the d orbitals

00:06:47.940 --> 00:06:52.240
again, that we just looked at,
we can look over here and say,

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:55.552
wow, some of those ligands
that are those negative point

00:06:55.552 --> 00:06:59.250
charges are basically
right there up

00:06:59.250 --> 00:07:01.020
against that d orbital.

00:07:01.020 --> 00:07:03.960
Pointing directly
toward the d orbital.

00:07:03.960 --> 00:07:05.880
So that's going to
be pretty repulsive.

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:09.690
The point charge is right
there next to the d orbital.

00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:12.580
This also has a point charge
kind of right toward it

00:07:12.580 --> 00:07:14.130
along z.

00:07:14.130 --> 00:07:18.670
But these, the point
charges, are on axis.

00:07:18.670 --> 00:07:22.470
Octahedral, you have
your ligands along z,

00:07:22.470 --> 00:07:24.840
along x, and along y.

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:28.260
But these sets of orbitals,
the negative point charges,

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:30.930
aren't pointing directly
at the d orbitals.

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:32.310
So one could think
about the fact

00:07:32.310 --> 00:07:35.820
that these are not going to
be not as much repulsion.

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:37.470
This is a lot of repulsion.

00:07:37.470 --> 00:07:40.770
All right, so let's go through
orbital set by orbital set

00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:44.250
and consider how
repulsive it's going to be

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:46.740
compared to the other orbitals.

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:51.110
OK, so if we look over here
at the octahedral case--

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:53.844
and I have both, these
drawings were on the first page

00:07:53.844 --> 00:07:54.510
of your handout.

00:07:54.510 --> 00:07:56.580
This is on the second page.

00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:57.830
But you can think about them.

00:07:57.830 --> 00:07:59.790
Here it's drawn more
where they're all

00:07:59.790 --> 00:08:01.590
drawn kind of the same way.

00:08:01.590 --> 00:08:04.260
Here it's sort of moved a
little so you can see better.

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:07.080
So we can keep both
of these in mind.

00:08:07.080 --> 00:08:10.320
So, again, the negative point
charges around the orbitals

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:10.890
here.

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:13.320
And on these drawings, I have
these little negative signs

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:17.527
pointing in to give you a sense
of where those negative point

00:08:17.527 --> 00:08:19.620
charge ligands are coming.

00:08:19.620 --> 00:08:23.670
So we have our dz2 and we can
see the negative point charge

00:08:23.670 --> 00:08:27.120
right toward this maximum
amplitude along z.

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:29.170
So that's going to be repulsive.

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:34.710
Dx2, y2, same thing, point
charges right toward these.

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:41.130
So the ligands point directly
at dz2 and dx2 minus y2.

00:08:41.130 --> 00:08:44.110
So there's a large
repulsion there.

00:08:44.110 --> 00:08:47.310
And, in this particular
case, in the octahedral case,

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:51.660
what turns out to be true,
both of these are stabilized.

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:54.900
And they're destabilized,
actually, by the same amount.

00:08:54.900 --> 00:08:58.170
And so that means that they
have the same energy, which

00:08:58.170 --> 00:09:00.120
we learned before,
means that there-- you

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:03.000
could say they're degenerate
with respect to each other.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.120
So both of these, big repulsion.

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:10.890
Both are destabilized by
those negative charges,

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:12.900
by the same amount.

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:16.950
And you have much more
repulsion, and much more

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:20.670
destabilization, for these
two orbitals compared

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:22.770
to the other set of orbitals.

00:09:22.770 --> 00:09:25.870
The ones that are
45 degrees off axis.

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:27.660
So now, let's look
at these and look

00:09:27.660 --> 00:09:30.150
at where the point charges are.

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:32.214
So this is the picture
in your handout.

00:09:32.214 --> 00:09:33.630
I just kind of put
these up there,

00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:37.200
too, so you can think about
where those point charges are

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:39.420
for octahedral geometry.

00:09:39.420 --> 00:09:41.790
So the ligands,
again now, are not

00:09:41.790 --> 00:09:46.050
pointing right at the orbitals.

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:47.820
They're off axis.

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:51.180
Because of ligands are on axis,
and the orbitals are off axis,

00:09:51.180 --> 00:09:53.470
and they're not directly
pointing toward each other.

00:09:53.470 --> 00:09:55.944
And so this is a
lot less repulsive

00:09:55.944 --> 00:09:57.360
than the other
situation where you

00:09:57.360 --> 00:09:59.340
have the ligands
and the orbitals,

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:02.440
both on axis, pointing
right toward each other.

00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:05.340
So now, this is why it's
important to know which

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:08.894
orbitals are 45 degree
off axis because we, now,

00:10:08.894 --> 00:10:10.560
can think about the
fact that there will

00:10:10.560 --> 00:10:13.680
be less repulsion in this case.

00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:20.790
So, we can say then, that
the xy, xz, and yz orbitals

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:28.560
are stabilized compared to
dz2 and dx2 minus y2 orbitals.

00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:31.810
And they're also stabilized
by the same amount.

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:33.810
So these are also degenerate.

00:10:33.810 --> 00:10:37.400
With respect to each other,
they have the same energy.

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:41.490
All right, so we have these
now two sets of orbital types.

00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:44.460
Two orbitals that
are destabilized,

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:48.630
and three orbitals that are
stabilized, compared to them.

00:10:48.630 --> 00:10:55.160
So now let's draw what's known
as an Octahedral Crystal Field

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:59.160
Splitting Diagram and think
about what's happening.

00:10:59.160 --> 00:11:01.150
So, I have some over there.

00:11:01.150 --> 00:11:02.630
Ignore those for now.

00:11:02.630 --> 00:11:05.550
I'm going to draw one over here.

00:11:05.550 --> 00:11:09.080
So first, we have
energy going up.

00:11:09.080 --> 00:11:13.070
And we have a situation we
first want to think about.

00:11:13.070 --> 00:11:17.510
What would be the case, say,
if you had ligands everywhere?

00:11:17.510 --> 00:11:21.230
Not just on the axis,
not octahedral geometry,

00:11:21.230 --> 00:11:22.710
but just everywhere.

00:11:22.710 --> 00:11:25.160
So if you had
ligands everywhere,

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:28.440
you would have
your 5 d orbitals,

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:29.810
all would have the same energy.

00:11:29.810 --> 00:11:31.940
Because all of them--
there's ligands everywhere--

00:11:31.940 --> 00:11:33.740
all of them would
be experiencing

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:36.320
the same amount of repulsion.

00:11:36.320 --> 00:11:42.060
So this would be the case for
a Spherical Crystal Field.

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:52.400
And I like to think about
this with this prop.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:54.006
I had this before
as an s orbital.

00:11:54.006 --> 00:11:55.380
It's convenient
for that as well.

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:59.540
But, really, what it is, is a
Hypothetical Spherical Crystal

00:11:59.540 --> 00:12:00.890
Field.

00:12:00.890 --> 00:12:03.320
Because these are
all little ligands.

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:05.750
And you can see these
little ligands are

00:12:05.750 --> 00:12:08.120
completely symmetric around.

00:12:08.120 --> 00:12:09.590
And if you feel
sort of the inside,

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:10.870
there's something in there.

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:13.220
Well that, of course,
is a metal ion.

00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:15.830
And these ligands are
completely around.

00:12:15.830 --> 00:12:19.250
So all the d
orbitals are equally

00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:22.340
feeling the repulsive
effects of these ligands.

00:12:22.340 --> 00:12:25.190
And so they all
have the same energy

00:12:25.190 --> 00:12:26.840
in this hypothetical case.

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:29.312
I was so excited when
I found this at CVS.

00:12:29.312 --> 00:12:30.770
And I went up and
I was, like, wow,

00:12:30.770 --> 00:12:34.430
you sell hypothetical
spherical crystal fields here.

00:12:34.430 --> 00:12:36.410
And the person was not amused.

00:12:36.410 --> 00:12:42.470
OK, so now what happens--
because this is not the case.

00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:43.267
This doesn't exist.

00:12:43.267 --> 00:12:44.350
This is just hypothetical.

00:12:44.350 --> 00:12:47.360
It looks like it
exists, but it doesn't.

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:49.410
This is what really exists.

00:12:49.410 --> 00:12:51.230
You have certain geometries.

00:12:51.230 --> 00:12:53.120
The ligands come
together with the metal

00:12:53.120 --> 00:12:55.160
and form particular geometries.

00:12:55.160 --> 00:12:57.860
And we already talked about
what those geometries are.

00:12:57.860 --> 00:12:59.750
There's not a whole
lot of variation.

00:12:59.750 --> 00:13:01.580
We get the same
kinds of geometries.

00:13:01.580 --> 00:13:04.700
And octahedral is the
most common geometry

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:06.650
for a transition metal complex.

00:13:06.650 --> 00:13:08.250
So what's going to happen here?

00:13:08.250 --> 00:13:12.860
So, the ligands will now split
the energy of the d orbitals.

00:13:12.860 --> 00:13:16.460
And three of them are
going to go down in energy.

00:13:16.460 --> 00:13:21.110
They're going to be stabilized
compared to the two that

00:13:21.110 --> 00:13:24.560
go up in energy.

00:13:24.560 --> 00:13:28.360
So the three that go--
are stabilized again,

00:13:28.360 --> 00:13:36.195
are dxy, dyz, and dxz.

00:13:36.195 --> 00:13:38.570
If you can't read this, it
all should be in your handout.

00:13:38.570 --> 00:13:41.020
So it's OK, you don't have
to read my handwriting.

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:44.810
And just kind of-- just
follow along in your notes.

00:13:44.810 --> 00:13:47.730
And then the ones that
have the most repulsion are

00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:54.770
dx2 minus y2 and dz2 up here.

00:13:54.770 --> 00:13:57.150
All right, so two
go up and energy.

00:13:57.150 --> 00:13:58.670
There's more repulsion.

00:13:58.670 --> 00:14:01.010
Three go down in energy.

00:14:01.010 --> 00:14:04.110
And instead of writing
all of those d's

00:14:04.110 --> 00:14:07.790
and x's and y's, they're little
abbreviations that people use.

00:14:07.790 --> 00:14:14.850
So they call these two
orbitals-- the eg orbitals.

00:14:14.850 --> 00:14:17.630
So those are the ones
that are destabilized.

00:14:17.630 --> 00:14:19.760
And the ones that
are stabilized are

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:23.510
called t2g orbitals,
which is going

00:14:23.510 --> 00:14:27.350
to make our nomenclature
easier later on.

00:14:27.350 --> 00:14:29.180
OK, these two again.

00:14:29.180 --> 00:14:32.034
Same energy I tried to draw
a straight line between them.

00:14:32.034 --> 00:14:33.950
They're degenerate with
respect to each other.

00:14:33.950 --> 00:14:37.040
These three of the same energy,
again, degenerate with respect

00:14:37.040 --> 00:14:38.180
to each other.

00:14:38.180 --> 00:14:43.400
And then the difference of
how much it's being split.

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:46.580
This energy difference
has a special name.

00:14:46.580 --> 00:14:49.610
It's sort of this delta sub o.

00:14:49.610 --> 00:14:51.960
And this is the octahedral.

00:14:54.970 --> 00:14:56.390
And that's the o.

00:14:56.390 --> 00:14:58.730
The o is octahedral.

00:14:58.730 --> 00:15:10.370
Crystal field splitting
energy because it's

00:15:10.370 --> 00:15:13.280
the energy that shows the
splitting of the crystal field.

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:16.620
So that's at least
a good name for it.

00:15:16.620 --> 00:15:21.020
All right, now,
overall this energy

00:15:21.020 --> 00:15:23.310
is going to be conserved.

00:15:23.310 --> 00:15:27.550
So the orbitals that go--
that are destabilized--

00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:30.270
and two go up and three go down.

00:15:30.270 --> 00:15:38.420
So we can also put that the two
that go up, go up by 3/5 times

00:15:38.420 --> 00:15:41.780
the octahedral splitting energy.

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:45.670
And the three that go
down-- are stabilized--

00:15:45.670 --> 00:15:49.750
go down by minus 2/5 times
the octahedral crystal

00:15:49.750 --> 00:15:51.010
field, splitting energy.

00:15:51.010 --> 00:15:52.330
So this is why I have
it in your notes,

00:15:52.330 --> 00:15:54.413
because you can't really
read my writing too well.

00:15:54.413 --> 00:15:59.020
So two go-- are
destabilized, up by 3/5.

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:03.910
Three, or stabilized,
down by 2/5 in energy.

00:16:03.910 --> 00:16:08.770
All right, so now what
controls the overall size

00:16:08.770 --> 00:16:10.744
of this splitting energy?

00:16:10.744 --> 00:16:11.410
How do you know?

00:16:11.410 --> 00:16:12.727
Is it a small splitting?

00:16:12.727 --> 00:16:14.560
Is this, you know,
should I have drawn this,

00:16:14.560 --> 00:16:15.768
that they're just a tiny bit?

00:16:15.768 --> 00:16:18.760
Or is it, like, could it be
a really large splitting?

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:21.920
What determines the splitting?

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:25.870
Or The magnitude of
this splitting energy.

00:16:25.870 --> 00:16:29.920
So what determines that
are the nature of ligands.

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:34.330
So some ligands are
really repulsive.

00:16:34.330 --> 00:16:35.740
Big splitting.

00:16:35.740 --> 00:16:38.740
Others-- eh-- you barely
notice they're there.

00:16:38.740 --> 00:16:40.000
Very little splitting.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.550
There's always some splitting.

00:16:42.550 --> 00:16:44.590
But it can be different.

00:16:44.590 --> 00:16:47.470
So the relative
ability of a ligand

00:16:47.470 --> 00:16:50.950
to split the crystal
field gives rise

00:16:50.950 --> 00:16:54.610
to what's known as the
Spectrochemical Series.

00:16:54.610 --> 00:16:57.760
So it's the relative
ability of common ligands

00:16:57.760 --> 00:17:02.020
to split the energies
of these d orbitals.

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:04.869
And this is what gives rise
to these beautiful colors.

00:17:04.869 --> 00:17:08.560
So all of those colors are
possible from cobalt compounds.

00:17:08.560 --> 00:17:10.150
Every single one of them.

00:17:10.150 --> 00:17:12.520
Because different ligands
will split the energy

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:16.460
different amounts, giving rise
to those different colors.

00:17:16.460 --> 00:17:19.750
So we have what's known
as Strong field ligands.

00:17:19.750 --> 00:17:22.810
And as that name would
suggest, Strong field ligands

00:17:22.810 --> 00:17:24.310
are going to have
a large splitting.

00:17:24.310 --> 00:17:25.780
They're very strong.

00:17:25.780 --> 00:17:29.530
They split to a large degree.

00:17:29.530 --> 00:17:35.110
And we have Weak field ligands.

00:17:35.110 --> 00:17:37.090
Weak field don't cause
much of a splitting.

00:17:37.090 --> 00:17:43.390
It's a small delta sub o,
small octahedral crystal

00:17:43.390 --> 00:17:46.780
field splitting energy.

00:17:46.780 --> 00:17:48.970
All right, so which
common ligands

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:52.780
